      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Power Burden</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul Sheridan letter on April 23 article sees possibility that deregulation of nation's electrical network may result in problems similar to those passengers encountered when airline industry was deregulated</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Deregulation or degeneration? The strains on the power grid make me wonder if electricity users will soon be seeing the type of supposed ''benefits'' that deregulation brought to airline travel.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Deregulation or degeneration? The strains on the power grid make me wonder if electricity users will soon be seeing the type of supposed ''benefits'' that deregulation brought to airline travel.</p>
        <p>As airline passengers, we have found less legroom, less service and many blackout periods for redeeming frequent-flier miles. The equivalents after power deregulation could be less spare capacity, poor distribution and (we hope not) more blackouts, period.</p>
        <p>Deregulation has brought no benefits to this electricity consumer.</p>
        <p>PAUL SHERIDAN  Brooklyn, April 24</p>
      </block>
